		<item>
		<title>Do you have more than good intentions?</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/48Days/~3/isUoFZBHwNI/</link>
		<comments>http://www.48days.com/2011/06/03/do-you-have-more-than-good-intentions/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 03 Jun 2011 08:00:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Dan Miller</dc:creator>

				<category><![CDATA[Personal Development]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[good intentions]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[margaret thatcher]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.48days.com/?p=7149</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<strong>No one would remember the Good Samaritan if he&#8217;d only had good intentions &#8211; he had money, too. – Margaret Thatcher</strong><strong> </strong>

Too often we assume that humanitarian or Godly work is done best by those in honorable professions like social worker, pastor, teacher, nurse, or non-profit employee and that the more money a person makes, the more removed they&#8230; <a href="http://www.48days.com/2011/06/03/do-you-have-more-than-good-intentions/" class="read_more">More...</a>]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><strong>No one would remember the Good Samaritan if he&#8217;d only had good intentions &#8211; he had money, too. – Margaret Thatcher</strong><strong> </strong></p>
<div>
<p>Too often we assume that humanitarian or Godly work is done best by those in honorable professions like social worker, pastor, teacher, nurse, or non-profit employee and that the more money a person makes, the more removed they are likely to be from “doing good.”  Be aware that if making money is one of your talents, you have added extreme leverage to your ability to do good in the world.</p>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
