		<item>
		<title>Would you do this for $50 an hour?</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/48Days/~3/_U7BEES_3rY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.48days.com/2011/05/12/would-you-accept-50-an-hour-for-this/#comments</comments>

		<pubDate>Thu, 12 May 2011 20:20:36 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Dan Miller</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Business Start-Up]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Finding Passion]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[No More Mondays]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[eker]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[millionaire mind]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[poor people]]></category>

		<category><![CDATA[rich people]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.48days.com/?p=6929</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[This morning I was scanning my tabs in T. Harv Eker’s book <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Secrets-Millionaire-Mind-Mastering-Wealth/dp/0060763280/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&#38;ie=UTF8&#38;qid=1305227188&#38;sr=1-1">Secrets of the Millionaire Mind</a>.  I read this book back in 2005 but like most books that I keep, I go back and review the highlights frequently.
One thing jumped out at me where the author says:  <em><strong>“There’s nothing wrong with getting a steady paycheck, unless it</strong></em>&#8230; <a href="http://www.48days.com/2011/05/12/would-you-accept-50-an-hour-for-this/" class="read_more">More...</a>]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This morning I was scanning my tabs in T. Harv Eker’s book <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Secrets-Millionaire-Mind-Mastering-Wealth/dp/0060763280/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1305227188&amp;sr=1-1">Secrets of the Millionaire Mind</a>.  I read this book back in 2005 but like most books that I keep, I go back and review the highlights frequently.</p>
<p>One thing jumped out at me where the author says:  <em><strong>“There’s nothing wrong with getting a steady paycheck, unless it interferes with your ability to earn what you’re worth.  There’s the rub.  It usually does.”</strong></em></p>
<p>Eker goes on to say that poor people prefer to be paid a steady salary or hourly wage.  They need the security of<a rel="attachment wp-att-6930" href="http://www.48days.com/2011/05/12/would-you-accept-50-an-hour-for-this/poor-person/"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-6930" title="poor-person" src="http://www.48days.com/wp-content/uploads/poor-person.gif" alt="" width="105" height="135" /></a> knowing that exactly the same amount of money is coming in at exactly the same time each week.  What they don’t realize is that this security comes with a price, and that price is this:  if you choose to get paid for your time, you are pretty much killing your chances for wealth.</p>
<p>Poor people trade their time for money.  Rich people prefer to get paid on the results they produce.   They work on commission or get a percentage of revenues.  Many choose to own their own business in some form.</p>
<p>As soon as you agree to be paid on results rather than time, you remove the ceiling to your income.</p>
<p>******************************************************</p>
<p>&#8220;As every millionaire knows, you&#8217;ll never gain wealth and financial security by working in a job you hate. <em><a href="http://www.48days.com/store/nmm-deluxe">No More Mondays</a></em> provides an inspiring roadmap on how to find meaningful work <em>and</em> financial freedom.&#8221;                       -<strong>T. Harv Eker, Author of #1 NY Times Bestseller <em>Secrets of the Millionaire Mind</em></strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
